1.DDL :  Data Definition Language

-> CREATE :- CREATE TABLE table_name (column1 data_type, column2 data_type, ...);
-> DROP :- DROP TABLE table_name;
-> ALTER :- ALTER TABLE table_name ADD COLUMN column_name data_type; (Alter the structure of the database)
-> TRUNCATE :- TRUNCATE TABLE table_name; (Remove all records from a table, including all spaces allocated for the records are removed.)

2.DQL : Data Query Language

-> SELECT :- SELECT column1, column2, ...FROM table_name WHERE condition; (It is used to retrieve data from the database)

3.DML : Data Manipulation Language

-> INSERT :- INSERT INTO table_name (column1, column2, ...) VALUES (value1, value2, ...); (Insert data into table.)
-> UPDATE :- UPDATE table_name SET column1 = value1, column2 = value2 WHERE condition; (Update existing data within a table)
-> DELETE :- DELETE FROM table_name WHERE condition; (Delete records from a database table)

4. DCL :- Data Control Language

-> GRANT :- GRANT privilege_type [(column_list)] ON [object_type] object_name TO user [WITH GRANT OPTION]; (Assigns new privileges to a user account, allowing access to specific database objects, actions, or functions.)

-> REVOKE :- REVOKE [GRANT OPTION FOR] privilege_type [(column_list)] ON [object_type] object_name FROM user [CASCADE]; (Removes previously granted privileges from a user account, taking away their access to certain database objects or actions.)

TCL :- Transaction Control Language

-> COMMIT :- COMMIT; (Saves all changes made during the transaction)

-> ROLLBACK :- ROLLBACK; (Undoes all changes made during the transaction)

-> SAVEPOINT :- SAVEPOINT savepoint_name;(Creates a savepoint within the current transaction)


----------------KEYS----------------
SUPER KEY : The set of one or more attributes (columns) that can uniquely identify a tuple (record) is known as Super Key.

CANDIDATE KEY : A candidate key is a minimal super key, meaning it can uniquely identify a record but contains no extra attributes.

ALTERNATE KEY : all the keys that are not selected as the primary key are considered alternate keys.

COMPOSITE KEY : Two or more attributes are used together to make a composite key .
